> x left side

The same doll is here, in a utilitarian waiting room. The doll has patches of skin where once there was wood. His eyes sometimes move ever so slightly. A man in a white lab coat opens the door and walks up to the doll.
The doctor clears his throat and says "I'm sorry to have to tell you this, sir, but complications have arose. We're not sure exactly...."
The doll's eyes dart about inside his head, looking for an escape.
You know he can't move. You know he can't speak. Not like this.
"Say something," you plead. "Say anything."
> x right side
> x right side
A child sits in a paltry excuse for a slave's room, drawing pictures of more innocent times with three crayons. He cannot be older than ten. His ankle is swollen as well as bruised and it's obvious he doesn't move his left arm very much or very fast. He takes care to not overuse his crayons. It is a learned behavior. He finishes what appears to be a drawing of a bird carrying someone away from a red house and towards the sun. He stands and slides the yellowing paper he drew upon into a loose border on the wall. It stays there. He backs away and looks at it, almost smiling. A door slams from somewhere in the house and he freezes in place, head cocked to the side. The sound of footsteps echoes and he darts under his rotting bed. Tears flow down his face, but he makes not a sound. He puts both arms up in front of his left shoulder and winces in pain at the motion. The sound of the door creaking open is louder than a gunshot.
> down
